The article discusses the historical significance of the march in Selma, Alabama in 1965, led by John Lewis, to secure the right to vote. It highlights the subsequent passage of the Voting Rights Act of 1965, but also notes that the strength of the law has been weakened over time by court decisions. The article expresses concern over current efforts in various states to make it harder to vote and suppress the vote. It calls for the passage of legislation, such as the John Lewis Voting Rights Advancement Act and the Freedom to Vote Act, to protect voting rights and election integrity. The article mentions that the Biden administration is committed to promoting voter participation, increasing access to the ballot, and protecting voting rights and election integrity. The U.S. Justice Department has also increased its voting rights enforcement staff. The article emphasizes the importance of the right to vote as a fundamental aspect of American democracy.